textRun.content: Review of both XXX and Gigs growth priorities for this year
Double click on any questions driven by the data - specific focus on subscription attach and churn
An overview of Gigs 2025 ARR forecast, inclusive of assumptions driving the number
A preview of new and upcoming Gigs product enhancements for the year
Successfully executing on these three important areas of focus will continue to push the XXXX <> Gigs partnership to new levels
Y/Y ARR trends look very similar this year vs last - dips in November, peaks in December / January, and a slow decline until back to school season begins
ARR growth rates are slowing - appears to be a factor of decreasing activation rates versus increased churn. Partially a factor of an increased size of base
New monthly subscriptions are trending down Y/Y
Concerns that declining subscription attach rate is main factor
Y/Y decline began in July 2024, and has not returned to growth since
Average Y/Y decline is -36% from July 2024 to today
For Discussion: declining overall sales vs declining subscription attach
Looking for insights from XYZ surrounding device sales trends over the last 10 months
ARPU has held consistent for ~5 months, with plan mix remaining largely unchanged
Assume that ARPU will increase significantly with launch XYZ product
Attach rate starts to sharply decline in November 2024 vs November 2023, and the trend continues today
Have user conversion rates diluted across products?
The timing of introducing these new plans seems to align with the declining attach rates
Did the plan price reductions attract a different customer, perhaps less likely to activate?
Visits to XYZ webpage doesn’t show a decline in web traffic, but something has fundamentally changed regarding conversion
All US-based XXX projects in the last 12 months
Opportunity to retain almost 10% of customers in this section of the funnel
Other similar Gigs Connect users see closer to 51% of customers who visit the website that make it through the full funnel to Subscription First Usage
Churn rates appear to be dropping back to rates we saw in summer of 2024
Price is not a key driving factor of voluntary Churn
Only ~2% mentioned price as a reason
(excluding no response and would rather not say)
10.49% - no need for device or subscription
Connect makes up the majority of activation volume
Most popular plan in Connect is the 24-month contract (34%), followed closely by pay-as-you-go (27%)
Significant mix of customers choosing the 24-month contract (44%), while the least popular plans remain the pay-upfront option (3%)
LTV (Lifetime Value) combines both plan value and subscription retention.
1-year Pay Upfront plans are the most profitable
2-year Pay Monthly plans are the least profitable
more appealing to users, but they generate $50 less per subscription compared to 1-year Pay Upfront
